Yep, but then, we should use `setState` in the `onChange`, and `onBlur` would change the scene variable object state instead. 

Setting the state on the component is cheap, and in this case, needed because we want to manage the temporal state as you mentioned. But we could safe a lot of other states updates from the scenes, if we just use `onBlur` for the model change.

 ```jsx
export function TextBoxVariableEditor({ variable }: TextBoxVariableEditorProps) {
  const { value } = variable.useState();
  const {textValue, setTextValueState} = useState(value);
  
  const onQueryChange = (event: React.FormEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    setTextValueState(event.currentTarget.value);
  };

  const onBlur = (event: React.FormEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    variable.setState({ value: textValue });
  };

  return <TextBoxVariableForm value={textValue} onChange={onQueryChange} onBlur={onBlur} />;
```

`queryLogsVolume(...)` creates custom data frame props called `absoluteRange` and `sourceQuery`

```typescript
            const logsVolumeCustomMetaData: LogsVolumeCustomMetaData = {
              logsVolumeType: LogsVolumeType.FullRange,
              absoluteRange: { from: range.from.valueOf(), to: range.to.valueOf() },
              datasourceName: datasource.name,
              sourceQuery: targets.find((dataQuery) => dataQuery.refId === sourceRefId)!,
            };
```

They are used by `canReuseSupplementaryQueryData` mentioned above https://github.com/grafana/grafana/blob/aa670280fc46b2d96e3096f1395e5145c715cb44/public/app/features/explore/state/query.ts#L878 to determine if the results can be reused without reissuing the query.

* `sourceQuery` is used to figure out if all queries are the same:

```typescript
const existingDataByRefId = mapValues(
    groupBy(
      supplementaryQueryData.data.map((dataFrame: DataFrame) => dataFrame.meta?.custom?.sourceQuery),
      'refId'
    ),
    head
  );
//...
  const allQueriesAreTheSame = deepEqual(newQueriesByRefId, existingDataByRefId);
```

* and `absoluteRange` is used to to check if saved results have a wider range than the newly requested one so all data can be reused:

```typescript
  const allResultsHaveWiderRange = supplementaryQueryData.data.every((data: DataFrame) => {
    const dataRange = data.meta?.custom?.absoluteRange;
    // Only first data frame in the response may contain the absolute range
    if (!dataRange) {
      return true;
    }
    const hasWiderRange = dataRange && dataRange.from <= selectedTimeRange.from && selectedTimeRange.to <= dataRange.to;
    return hasWiderRange;
  });
```

Eventually, queries are reused if:

```  return allSupportZoomingIn && allQueriesAreTheSame && allResultsHaveWiderRange;```

